04366nam a22005535i 9780804777827DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20202011cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047778277 a10.1515/97808047778272doi  a(DE-B1597)564550  a(OCoLC)1178769375  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aN9165.F8K37 2011 7aHIS0130002bisacsh04a363.6/90944090441 aKarlsgodt, Elizabeth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDefending National Treasures :bFrench Art and Heritage Under Vichy /cElizabeth Karlsgodt. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2011  a1 online resource (404 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1. Cultural Affairs under Vichy -- t2. Defending French Style and Beauty -- t3. Exodus -- t4. Museums Fit for France -- t5. Saving Historic Sites -- t6. Archeology and the National Revolution -- t7. Recycling French Heroes -- t8. Endangered Local Patrimony -- t9. Jewish Art Collections -- t10. Art as a Negotiating Tool -- tConclusion -- tAppendix A. Primary National Museum Storage Depots, 1939-1940 -- tAppendix B. Provincial Museums in 1939 Protection Plan -- tAppendix C. Evacuation of Provincial Collections, 1941-1944 -- tAppendix D. Composition of the National Museum Advisory Councils -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDefending National Treasures explores the fate of art and cultural heritage during the Nazi occupation of France. The French cultural patrimony was a crucial locus of power struggles between German and French leaders and among influential figures in each country. Karlsgodt examines the preservation policy that the Vichy regime enacted in an assertion of sovereignty over French art museums, historic monuments, and archeological sites. The limits to this sovereignty are apparent from German appropriations of public statues, Jewish-owned art collections, and key "Germanic" works of art from French museums. A final chapter traces the lasting impact of the French wartime reforms on preservation policy. In Defending National Treasures, Karlsgodt introduces the concept of patrimania to reveal examples of opportunism in art preservation. During the war, French officials sought to acquire coveted artwork from Jewish collections for the Louvre and other museums; in the early postwar years, they established a complicated guardianship over unclaimed art recovered from Germany. A cautionary tale for our own times, Defending National Treasures examines the ethical dimensions of museum acquisitions in the ongoing noble quest to preserve great works of art.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aArt and statezFrancexHistoryy20th century. 0aArt museumszFrancexHistoryy20th century. 0aArt treasures in warzFrancexHistoryy20th century. 0aCultural propertyxProtectionzFrancexHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xConfiscations and contributionszFrance. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xDestruction and pillagezFrance. 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804777827zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804777827423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804777827.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles